entry.title: [Topics] pad topics header to make it harder to expose information via its length
entry.content:
What:

Switch to a different header format to allow padding.

Example: "t=(1;v=chrome.1:1:2), p=P00000000000"



The total length of the inner topics list plus the padding depends on the number of distinct version in the underlying epochs:

- If it's 0 or 1, use 27

("100;v=chrome.1:1:10 200 300")

- If it's 2, use 43

("100;v=chrome.1:1:10 200;v=chrome.1:1:20 300")

- If it's 3, use 59

("100;v=chrome.1:1:10 200;v=chrome.1:1:20 300;v=chrome.1:1:30")



This assumes maximum 3 digit topic ID, 2 digit model version,

and 1 digit config version and taxonomy version.



Why: Servers typically have a GET request size limit e.g. 8KB, and

will return an error when the limit is reached. An attacker can rely

this to learn the number of topics for a different origin.

VideoTrackAdapter drops frames in order to make sure that the output frame rate is close to the target frame rate despite an arbitrary

input frame rate.



However, too many frames were dropped occasionally. After digging into this I've found that the logic was very sensitive to jitter in the

input.



If the input timestamps are 10 fps with the following pattern:

0, 10 ms, 200 ms, 210 ms, 400 ms, 410 ms, 600 ms, 610 ms,...



and the max fps is set to 5 fps, VideoTrackAdapter produced something

like this:

0, 400 ms, 1000 ms, 1800 ms, 2610 ms, 3800 ms, 4800 ms, 5800 ms,...



which is roughly 1 fps. With the current CL, the output is as expected:

0, 200 ms, 400 ms, 600 ms, 800 ms, etc.

entry.title: [GridNG] Don't consider a subgridded axis size in ExpandFlexibleTracks
entry.content:
1. Fixing a bug where `ExpandFlexibleTracks` considered the contribution

size of a subgrid in its subgridded axis, triggering a DCHECK when

its `NGGridLayoutTrackCollection` is not able perform the sizing

algorithm since it's inherited by the subgrid's parent grid.



From https://drafts.csswg.org/css-grid-2/#subgrid-size-contribution,

in this scenario we should treat the subgrid contribution size as

empty and not consider it when resolving the size of an `fr`.



2. Adding test coverage to the WPT suite for this issue.



Bug: 1447363

entry.title: media: win camera capture zero copy
entry.content:
This CL is designed to allow Chromium to use shared MediaEngineCapture

passed textures on windows, thus reducing one time texture copy which

will benefit video conference use case.



Specifically, the camera capture feature in Chromium is by far

"1-copy capture". What we get from Frameserver will be firstly copied

to the GMB allocated by Chromium(internal allocation) and then it's

consumed for renderer/encoder. This CL uses the shared texture from

MFCaptureEngine, thus removing the only 1-copy we currently have in

Chromium, and reuse the share_handle and token for same texture by

SetPrivateData/GetPrivateData.



This CL also changed the buffer pool size from 30 to 10 since it's

confirmed that MFCaptureEngine may terminate the capture with

MF_E_SAMPLEALLOCATOR_EMPTY error if more than 10 buffers are held by

the client, and usually there are 3-5 frames in flight, unless

there's some micro-freeze in the renderer or the gpu service.



Tested this CL on mac, no regression in behavior.



Another CL will manage the lifetime of IMFBuffer to correctly reuse

texture.



Feature command:

--enable

features=MediaFoundationD3D11VideoCapture,

MediaFoundationD3D11VideoCaptureZeroCopy



Test command:

1. autoninja -C out\Default content_unittests

2. content_unittests.exe --

gtest_filter=All/VideoCaptureBufferPoolTest.BufferPoolExternalWin/*



Bug: 1120900, 1430048

entry.title: [SuperSize] Store added / removed files in .sizediff; use this in Viewer.
entry.content:
In SuperSize Viewer, dense diffs deduces file addition / removal by

whether its symbols are all-add or all-remove. In Tree View, this is

shown as "+" or "-" icon for file nodes.



Unfortunately, the above approach doesn't work for sparse diffs, since

unchanged symbols are omitted. Thus sparse diff Tree View file nodes

don't show "+" or "-" icons.



To improve consistency, this CL updates .sizediff format to store info

so files addition / removal can be deduced. Contrary to the proposal in

crbug.com/1047572, we're storing the info as optional compressed lists

of removed and added files files in .sizediff:

* In .sizediff JSON:

* Add optional field "removed_sources_length" for length of GZIP

compressed data for removed file.

* Add optional field "added_sources_length" for length of GZIP

compressed data for added file.

* If |removed_sources_length| is present: Store GZIP compressed data of

the file list as multi-line plain text, with the first line storing

n = number of entries, followed by n lines of ASCII encoded file

paths.

* If |added_sources_length| is present: Repeat for added files.

* (GZIP sparse "before" size file and sparse "after" size file follow).



SuperSize / Caspian are updated to write / read the new .sizediff

format, which is a generalization of the old format (where the optional

fields are simply omitted).



Old versions of SuperSize / Caspian will be UNABLE to read .sizediff

augmented with the new fields / data.



In SuperSize / Caspian, |removed_sources| / |added_sources| lists are

placed under DeltaSizeInfo instead of "before" / "after" SizeInfo, since

these lists are derived from comparing.



Unfortunately, the above leads to awkwardness in SuperSize-Console,

which considers DeltaSizeInfo to derive purely from "before" / "after"

SizeInfo. We handle mismatch by simply dropping the new lists after

parsing them; these lists are mainly for the Viewer anyway.



As for Caspian, |removed_sources| / |added_sources| lists are loaded and

used to assign |diffStatus| field for TreeNode. This in turn leads to

desired "+" or "-" icons in file nodes. No Viewer JS code needs to be

changed; for simplicity we don't even send these lists to the Viewer.



Details for SuperSize (Python):

* models.py:

* DeltaSymbolGroup: Add GetEntireAddOrRemoveSources() to compute

|removed_sources| and |added_sources| from delta symbols.

* DeltaSizeInfo: Add |removed_sources| and |added_sources| as lists.

* diff.py: Call the above and store into DeltaSymbolGroup.

* file_format.py:

* Add helpers {_Save,_Load}CompressedStringList().

* {Save,Load}DeltaSizeInfo(): Write / read the lists. Empty lists are

omitted.

* archive.py: LoadAndPostProcessDeltaSizeInfo(): Discard result.



Details for Caspian (C++):

* file_format.{h,cc}: Update ParseDiffSizeInfo() to read new data.

* models.{h,cc}:

* DeltaSizeInfo: Add lists |removed_sources|, |added_sources|.

* NodeStats: Add |imposed_diff_status| as alternative to

GetGlobalDiffStatus().

* TreeNode::WriteIntoJson(): For sparse diffs, pass

|imposed_diff_status| to Viewer as "diffStatus" if non-default.

* tree_builder.{h,cc}:

* TreeBuilder: Add |source_to_diff_status_| to map from source file to

{kRemoved,kAdded} status. Assigned in CTOR that takes DeltaSizeInfo.

* TreeBuilder::AddFileEntry(): On instantiating file TreeNode, assign

|file_node->node_state.imposed_diff_status| if successfully

matched against |source_to_diff_status_|.

* caspian_web.cc: Store |removed_sources|, |added_sources| globally

(alongside other global data).

* cli.cc: Update Diff() usage; print file lists in validatediff.

* diff_tests.cc: Update Diff() usage, also dedup code by extracting

class DiffTest and use TEST_F().

entry.title: [GridNG] Prevent zero-sized set track counts at non-zero indices
entry.content:
This CL fixes a a divide-by-zero in `ComputeTrackSizeRepeaterForRange`,

but the fix is nowhere near that code. The basic premise being violated

is that sets collections should always have the first set with a

`track_count` of 0, and no other indices should have a `track_count` of

zero. This is because the first set isn't actually a track

representation, it's for accumulated extra margin.



This premise gets violated when copying the set values from the parent

with opposite-direction children, which I added in

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4484336



The proper mitigation for this is to take the offset from the current

index, but the track count from the *next* index for opposite direction

subgrids. This will properly account for the initial entry with zero

tracks.

entry.title: Revert handling of transient children when bubble launcher hides
entry.content:
Reverts CL:4456250 and CL:4518164 that were attempting to unparent and

close transient child windows when hiding bubble launcher to ensure

uninstall dialogs parented to the app list window gets closed.



This ended up causing a crash in touch_selection_controller

implementation (which does not expect the editing handle view widget to

get closed before the associated texfield loses focus). Arguably,

TouchSelectionController could be made more robust to this cases, or we

could have app list bubble presenter close transient children later on

(after the bubble is actually hidden), but given that this needs to be

fixed on other branches, reverting to the old behaviour (which though

not ideal was around for a while) is safer.



BUG=1448682, b:264690245

entry.title: Fix TabGroupSubMenuModel crash
entry.content:
Fixes a crash where the tabstrip may have been modified when the tab

group submenu was open which may invalidate the context index.



We now guard that the context index (the tab we clicked on) exists in

the current TabStripModel.



Additional changes:

- Adds comments to the code to make it clear what is happening throughout

the function.

- Removes unneeded DCHECK & selection indices variables.

- Renames the variable tab -> tab_index for conciseness.

- Removes temporary object in emplace_back call for menu_item_infos.
